How it works

  A BVH is a binary tree of axis-aligned bounding boxes (AABBs). Each leaf holds
   one (or a few) objects. Each internal node's box encloses all its children.
  Ray traversal skips entire subtrees when the ray misses a node's box → O(log
  N) instead of O(N) per ray.

  What you'd need to add

  1. AABB class — axis-aligned bounding box with a fast ray-box intersection
  test (slab method)
  2. BVHNode implementing SceneObject — each node holds an AABB and either two
  children or a leaf object
  3. SceneObject.getBounds() — each object returns its AABB (trivial for
  spheres: center ± radius)
  4. Build step — sort objects along the longest axis, split in half, recurse

  New files:
  - AABB.java — Axis-aligned bounding box with slab-method ray intersection test
   and fromPoints() factory for easy construction
  - BVHNode.java — Binary tree with build (sort by longest axis, split in half)
  and intersect (skip subtrees when ray misses box)

  Modified files:
  - SceneObject.java — Added getBounds() to the interface
  - Sphere.java — getBounds() returns center ± radius
  - Plane.java — getBounds() returns null (infinite, tested linearly)
  - Prism.java — Computes AABB from 6 prism vertices during construction
  - Cube.java — Computes AABB from 8 corners during construction
  - Sky.java — getBounds() returns null
  - Scene.java — Builds BVH lazily on first intersect() call. Bounded objects go
   through the BVH (O(log N)), unbounded objects (planes) are tested linearly

