  The problem: Water's Fresnel reflectance at the rainbow angle is only ~2%.
  With 1000 samples per pixel, only ~12 rays per pixel follow the internal
  reflection path that creates the rainbow. This is far too few — the rainbow
  signal is buried in noise.

  The fix — importance sampling: Instead of sampling reflection with the true
  Fresnel probability (2%), we sample with max(fresnelProb, 25%). When we choose
   reflection, the throughput is scaled down by fresnelProb / sampleProb to
  compensate. When we choose refraction, the throughput is scaled up by
  (1-fresnelProb) / (1-sampleProb). This is mathematically unbiased — the
  expected result is identical, but ~250 rays per pixel now follow the rainbow
  path instead of 12, dramatically reducing variance on the caustic.